This is a 300 horsepower
electric motor,

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:37.870
but it's in a 6,000
ton submarine.

00:18:37.870 --> 00:18:40.510
So this electric motor just
barely pushes the submarine

00:18:40.510 --> 00:18:41.650
through the water.

00:18:41.650 --> 00:18:42.660
And there's two speeds.

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:43.780
So what's happening
is when you're

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:46.150
operating the electric motor
with the reactor shut down,

00:18:46.150 --> 00:18:48.490
you're draining the
battery pretty quickly.

00:18:48.490 --> 00:18:52.450
And there's a race to
get the reactor started.

00:18:52.450 --> 00:18:54.220
So here we are,
we're running on.

00:18:54.220 --> 00:18:56.020
We're at 1/3.

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:58.790
We shut down the reactors,
the very first drill.

00:18:58.790 --> 00:19:01.439
I'm standing in
the control room.

00:19:01.439 --> 00:19:02.980
The officer has been
on the submarine

00:19:02.980 --> 00:19:06.669
the longest, Bill Green is
his name, is controlling this.

00:19:06.669 --> 00:19:07.960
And he's doing the right thing.

00:19:07.960 --> 00:19:10.261
He's ahead 1/3,
conserving the battery.

00:19:10.261 --> 00:19:12.010
Now in every other
submarine I've been on,

00:19:12.010 --> 00:19:14.110
there was two speeds
to this electric motor.

00:19:14.110 --> 00:19:18.790
But unbeknownst to me, on the
Santa Fe, there's only one.

00:19:18.790 --> 00:19:20.445
So I'm thinking,
hey, if we speed up,

00:19:20.445 --> 00:19:22.070
it's going to drain
the battery faster,

00:19:22.070 --> 00:19:24.320
it's gonna put some
stress on the team.

00:19:24.320 --> 00:19:25.600
Train harder.

00:19:25.600 --> 00:19:27.550
And so I suggest, hey,
why don't we speed up

00:19:27.550 --> 00:19:29.770
on this electric motor?

00:19:29.770 --> 00:19:31.240
And he gives the order.

00:19:31.240 --> 00:19:32.740
But the sailor
sitting at this panel

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:36.190
