But I talked to my
team and we said,

00:22:22.860 --> 00:22:24.870
you know what, it's not that.

00:22:24.870 --> 00:22:26.610
We're just missing something.

00:22:26.610 --> 00:22:28.330
And here's the model
we came up with.

00:22:28.330 --> 00:22:31.500
We said, I've given
too much control.

00:22:31.500 --> 00:22:34.380
I was irresponsibly
giving control.

00:22:34.380 --> 00:22:37.260
And what I really needed to do
was tune the level of control

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:41.730
to how much they knew about
their jobs and the clarity

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:42.870
of purpose.

00:22:42.870 --> 00:22:45.672
This is the why that
Simon Sineks talks about.

00:22:45.672 --> 00:22:47.130
Because if you say,
you get to make

00:22:47.130 --> 00:22:48.713
a decision on which
customer you call,

00:22:48.713 --> 00:22:52.380
you could talk, forget the
script, just talk to him.

00:22:52.380 --> 00:22:55.590
You need to know what
we're trying to achieve.

00:22:55.590 --> 00:22:58.912
And so we now say leaders tune.

00:22:58.912 --> 00:22:59.620
The word is tune.

00:22:59.620 --> 00:23:02.600
We tune the level of control
and we invite the team

00:23:02.600 --> 00:23:04.840
to higher and higher levels.

00:23:04.840 --> 00:23:06.831
So we don't empower teams.

00:23:06.831 --> 00:23:08.580
First of all, teams
are already empowered.

00:23:08.580 --> 00:23:11.119
It's inside every human being.

00:23:11.119 --> 00:23:13.410
But what we do is we tune
the empowerment to the levels

00:23:13.410 --> 00:23:15.450
of competence and control.

00:23:15.450 --> 00:23:17.950
Otherwise, it's just
irresponsibility.

00:23:17.950 --> 00:23:19.740
Now, this is Dr. Stephen Covey.

00:23:19.740 --> 00:23:22.000
He wrote "7 Habits of Highly
Effective People," which

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:24.654
is an awesome book and
I was a huge Covey fan.

00:23:24.654 --> 00:23:26.070
And what happened
on the submarine

00:23:26.070 --> 00:23:28.170
was things started going
really, really well.

00:23:28.170 --> 00:23:29.900
Every single sailor
in the next 12 months

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:32.460
re-enlisted, 35 out of 35.

00:23:32.460 --> 00:23:34.547
And we were evaluated
by the Navy,

00:23:34.547 --> 00:23:36.630
and the crew of the Santa
Fe got the highest score

00:23:36.630 --> 00:23:38.700
in the history of
the inspection team.

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:41.440
They never had records
that had a higher score.

00:23:41.440 --> 00:23:43.560
And everyone was
really confused.

00:23:43.560 --> 00:23:47.400
How did that crew that
was so bad get so good?

00:23:47.400 --> 00:23:50.160
And the rest of the Navy
thought I was just giving some

00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:53.520
really great orders.

00:23:53.520 --> 00:23:57.250
My peers would call me
and say, congratulations,

00:23:57.250 --> 00:24:00.070
you must be making some
really good orders.

00:24:00.070 --> 00:24:02.700
I'd just be like, I'm actually
trying this new thing.

00:24:02.700 --> 00:24:06.660
I'm not giving orders, not
telling them what to do.

00:24:06.660 --> 00:24:07.990
They're like, what?

00:24:07.990 --> 00:24:10.170
Like, yeah, nevermind.

00:24:10.170 --> 00:24:13.540
Because from their paradigm,
it just didn't work.

00:24:13.540 --> 00:24:16.470
But what we had done, I realized
that later what we'd done

00:24:16.470 --> 00:24:20.070
is gone from one leader
and 134 followers,

00:24:20.070 --> 00:24:22.320
and one thinker
and 134 doers, just

00:24:22.320 --> 00:24:26.100
like that picture of the
factory to 135 active thinking,

00:24:26.100 --> 00:24:29.940
passionate, creative people,
which I call leadership.

00:24:29.940 --> 00:24:33.707
My role as the
captain was simply

00:24:33.707 --> 00:24:35.790
to create this environment
where people could come

00:24:35.790 --> 00:24:37.360
to work and just be their best.

00:24:37.360 --> 00:24:38.430
That's all I did.

00:24:38.430 --> 00:24:41.410
All day long, all day long.

00:24:41.410 --> 00:24:42.870
And it worked amazing.

00:24:42.870 --> 00:24:46.320
And so Dr. Covery
watched the ship.

00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:47.670
And now we were about intent.

00:24:47.670 --> 00:24:49.170
I'm stopping telling
you what to do,

00:24:49.170 --> 00:24:52.855
but you've got to come to me to
tell me what you intend to do.

00:24:52.855 --> 00:24:54.380
If I'm not telling
you what to do

00:24:54.380 --> 00:24:56.550
and you're not doing anything,
then I'm leaning back

00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:58.230
and you're not leaning in to me.

00:24:58.230 --> 00:25:00.240
So I actually think
leaders lean back

00:25:00.240 --> 00:25:02.850
and the team leans forward.

00:25:02.850 --> 00:25:06.540
So Dr. Covey saw how
we talked to each other

00:25:06.540 --> 00:25:09.540
and he said this is how I
think you guys are doing it.

00:25:09.540 --> 00:25:11.790
When people come up and say,
well, tell me what to do,

00:25:11.790 --> 00:25:14.275
we resist telling
them what to do.

00:25:14.275 --> 00:25:16.650
The instinct is you want to,
because you know the answer,

00:25:16.650 --> 00:25:21.060
and it's so psychologically
fulfilling to say yes, do this.

00:25:21.060 --> 00:25:23.460
Boy, I solved so many
people's problems today.

00:25:23.460 --> 00:25:25.900
Well, don't I feel
good about that.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:27.810
And we say, well,
what do you see?

00:25:27.810 --> 00:25:30.050
This is description.

00:25:30.050 --> 00:25:31.320
What do you think?

00:25:31.320 --> 00:25:32.670
What do you think we should do?

00:25:32.670 --> 00:25:33.920
Hey, what do you intend to do?

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:35.620
Maybe you should just do it.

00:25:35.620 --> 00:25:36.690
Depends on what it is.

00:25:36.690 --> 00:25:39.420
We would just invite people
and we'd have close the latter,

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:42.270
and you guys have a card
that describes how this went.

00:25:42.270 --> 00:25:43.620
But this is how you tune it.

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:46.795
This is why you can
dial it exactly.

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:52.320
Question for you.

00:25:52.320 --> 00:25:56.010
So you've got
someone on your team

00:25:56.010 --> 00:25:59.700
and they're down there,
tell me what to do.

00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:04.080
You probably don't have any
of these people at Google,

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:05.527
but just imagine you did.

00:26:05.527 --> 00:26:07.110
They're like, well,
what do I do here?

00:26:07.110 --> 00:26:08.165
And you're inviting them.

00:26:08.165 --> 00:26:09.540
You say, well,
what do you think?

00:26:09.540 --> 00:26:11.220
What should we do?

00:26:11.220 --> 00:26:13.500
And they just seem stuck
at tell me what to do.

00:26:13.500 --> 00:26:15.868
What keeps people stuck
at tell me what to do.

00:26:15.868 --> 00:26:18.284
Go ahead and send a bunch of
words, let's see what we get.

00:26:21.060 --> 00:26:22.560
And you can type
in a bunch of words

00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:24.665
and hit enter and have
all the words come up.

00:26:24.665 --> 00:26:25.790
Get a whole bunch of words.

00:26:32.729 --> 00:26:33.770
Let's see what we've got.

00:26:33.770 --> 00:26:37.850
Confusion, confidence,
disillusionment, understanding,

00:26:37.850 --> 00:26:42.230
inexperience, mistakes, pride,
misunderstanding, status,

00:26:42.230 --> 00:26:43.130
superiority.

00:26:46.280 --> 00:26:49.910
And fear.

00:26:49.910 --> 00:26:53.570
Fear is always the
biggest problem.

00:26:53.570 --> 00:26:56.420
I've done this to
over 100 audiences

00:26:56.420 --> 00:26:59.269
in 20 different countries
and every single time,

00:26:59.269 --> 00:27:00.560
fear has been the biggest word.

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:03.500
In fact, if I aggregate
those 100 speeches,

00:27:03.500 --> 00:27:05.941
this is what it looks like.

00:27:05.941 --> 00:27:07.940
The reason people are not
saying what they think

00:27:07.940 --> 00:27:09.339
is not because they don't know.

00:27:09.339 --> 00:27:11.130
It's because they're
afraid of being wrong,

00:27:11.130 --> 00:27:12.500
they're afraid of
being laughed at,

00:27:12.500 --> 00:27:14.180
they're afraid of being the
person who thinks differently

00:27:14.180 --> 00:27:16.460
from everybody else, afraid
of taking responsibility,

00:27:16.460 --> 00:27:17.930
whatever it happens to be.

00:27:17.930 --> 00:27:22.340
And this gets me to the
next leadership myth.

00:27:22.340 --> 00:27:25.250
I thought my job as a leader
was to quote "motivate" my team.

00:27:25.250 --> 00:27:28.370
And a lot of times,
motivate meant add stress.

00:27:28.370 --> 00:27:29.780
Come on, guys, we can do it.

00:27:32.900 --> 00:27:35.290
What leaders need to do
is make it feel safe.

00:27:35.290 --> 00:27:37.010
Because fear is the problem.

00:27:37.010 --> 00:27:40.070
So the antidote
to fear is safety.

00:27:40.070 --> 00:27:44.770
So my job all day long
was to say yeah, it's OK.

00:27:44.770 --> 00:27:46.400
Express that in probabilities.

00:27:49.020 --> 00:27:53.140
Just give me a scale, 1 to 10,
how do you think about that.

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:55.790
And really ask questions in
a way that made it feel safe.

00:27:55.790 --> 00:27:57.459
I'll give you a
very small example.

00:27:57.459 --> 00:27:59.000
People would come
up to me and they'd

00:27:59.000 --> 00:28:01.790
say, well, I think we should
do this, are you sure.

00:28:01.790 --> 00:28:04.520
No, that doesn't feel safe.

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:09.170
No, I'm not sure to be honest.

00:28:09.170 --> 00:28:11.440
Or they have this
false bravado, yes, I'm

00:28:11.440 --> 00:28:14.580
sure, which is always wrong.

00:28:14.580 --> 00:28:19.040
So what's your sense of
enthusiasm over this.

00:28:19.040 --> 00:28:21.300
And we'd ask
questions, if you want

00:28:21.300 --> 00:28:23.120
a clue for asking a
question, always try

00:28:23.120 --> 00:28:25.250
to put how at the beginning.

00:28:25.250 --> 00:28:27.640
How likely it is we're going
to launch a product on time.

00:28:27.640 --> 00:28:30.406
Not will we launch on time.

00:28:30.406 --> 00:28:31.280
We just make it safe.

00:28:31.280 --> 00:28:34.160
And all day long, trying to
make it safe for my people

00:28:34.160 --> 00:28:36.080
to share what they
thought, even if it was

00:28:36.080 --> 00:28:38.340
potentially wrong or different.

00:28:38.340 --> 00:28:40.796
Especially if it were different.

00:28:40.796 --> 00:28:42.620
Here we are, we're
fighting a fire.

00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:45.506
We were not very good at this
when I first got to the ship.

00:28:45.506 --> 00:28:46.880
And then we'd sit
in a room, we'd

00:28:46.880 --> 00:28:51.920
do a retrospective or a critique
or a fact finding, whatever

00:28:51.920 --> 00:28:53.210
you want to call it.

00:28:53.210 --> 00:28:54.665
And I heard a lot of that.

00:28:54.665 --> 00:28:56.790
I was listening to the
language and they would say,

00:28:56.790 --> 00:28:59.649
well, they didn't
pressurize the hose,

00:28:59.649 --> 00:29:01.940
they didn't change the
batteries on the thermal imager.

00:29:01.940 --> 00:29:04.280
They hung the gear up
twisted, so it took me

00:29:04.280 --> 00:29:06.320
longer to get there
than it should have.

00:29:06.320 --> 00:29:07.850
There was all this
they, referring

00:29:07.850 --> 00:29:11.050
to all these other people
on board the submarine.

00:29:11.050 --> 00:29:14.230
There was they by rank,
there was they by department.

00:29:14.230 --> 00:29:18.050
And I got upset one
day with this they.

00:29:18.050 --> 00:29:19.940
Because it didn't
feel like a team.

00:29:19.940 --> 00:29:22.730
I said there's no
more they on Santa Fe.

00:29:22.730 --> 00:29:24.920
It rhymed.

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:26.570
So that was good.

00:29:26.570 --> 00:29:27.827
You can only use the word we.

00:29:27.827 --> 00:29:29.660
Very next day, the
engineer walked up to me.

00:29:29.660 --> 00:29:32.630
Now he wants to tell me
that the supply department,

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:35.360
he's in charge of engineering,
that the supply department

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:38.317
has ordered the wrong part.

00:29:38.317 --> 00:29:39.650
You know what I'm talking about.

00:29:39.650 --> 00:29:40.580
So he comes up to me.

00:29:40.580 --> 00:29:42.197
He says, Captain,
I've got bad news.

00:29:42.197 --> 00:29:44.030
I'm kind of hanging out
in the control room,

00:29:44.030 --> 00:29:45.030
like I would usually do.

00:29:45.030 --> 00:29:46.890
He says, Captain,
I've got bad news.

00:29:46.890 --> 00:29:49.020
I said yeah, what do you got?

00:29:49.020 --> 00:29:54.680
Says, Captain, we can't
fix the pump, because th--

00:29:54.680 --> 00:29:59.160
th-- he wants to say
they, but he can't.

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:04.520
So he says because we
ordered the wrong part.

00:30:04.520 --> 00:30:08.540
I kind of look at him, he
looks at me, I look at him,

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:11.180
and he just goes like.

00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:13.520
It was super awesome.

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:15.230
There's no blame
in recommendations.

00:30:15.230 --> 00:30:17.030
So when I go into
organizations, I

00:30:17.030 --> 00:30:19.160
listen for what I call
the we they boundary.

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:21.490
Like where is it we?

00:30:21.490 --> 00:30:25.719
Like we're in the engineering,
but they're in marketing.

00:30:25.719 --> 00:30:27.260
And where does it
go from we to they?

00:30:27.260 --> 00:30:28.490
Because as soon as you
go from we to they,

00:30:28.490 --> 00:30:30.410
that's where the
team boundary ends.

00:30:30.410 --> 00:30:32.870
And so the problem is
most people say well,

00:30:32.870 --> 00:30:34.790
think like a team.

00:30:34.790 --> 00:30:38.660
Here's some posters
that tell us.

00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:42.000
Send some emails to
encourage people, whatever.

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.540
That doesn't make team
performance happen.

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:45.980
We just said the word we.

00:30:45.980 --> 00:30:48.770
And six months later, we
had rewired our brains

00:30:48.770 --> 00:30:49.930
and it felt like a team.

00:30:49.930 --> 00:30:51.670
People would come down the
ship and say oh, it's amazing,

00:30:51.670 --> 00:30:52.850
it feels like a team.

00:30:52.850 --> 00:30:54.830
They wouldn't even know why.

00:30:54.830 --> 00:30:57.810
But it was because we
now became one big we.

00:30:57.810 --> 00:31:01.100
And so this gets me to there's
the no they on Santa Fe.

00:31:01.100 --> 00:31:06.260
Myth number five, which is teams
think their way to new action.

00:31:06.260 --> 00:31:08.516
Any change management that
I've seen starts with well,

00:31:08.516 --> 00:31:10.890
we've got to create a mindset
and blah, blah, blah, blah,

00:31:10.890 --> 00:31:11.390
blah.

00:31:11.390 --> 00:31:14.120
That's I'm going to think my way
to new behavior, which I don't

00:31:14.120 --> 00:31:15.500
think is the way it works.

00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:17.840
We behave our way
to new thinking.

00:31:17.840 --> 00:31:20.150
A perfect example is
in your lunchroom.

00:31:20.150 --> 00:31:23.210
Because Google did a study,
because they wanted more team

00:31:23.210 --> 00:31:23.732
interaction.

00:31:23.732 --> 00:31:25.940
They found out they had all
these little small tables

00:31:25.940 --> 00:31:26.979
in all the lunchrooms.

00:31:26.979 --> 00:31:28.395
So when people go
to lunch, they'd

00:31:28.395 --> 00:31:31.010
only sit with two or
three people at most.

00:31:31.010 --> 00:31:33.279
You replace them and now
you have those long tables.

00:31:33.279 --> 00:31:34.820
It's because of when
you go to lunch,

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:36.980
now you can sit with
bigger groups of people.

00:31:36.980 --> 00:31:39.079
We don't give people a lecture.

00:31:39.079 --> 00:31:41.120
We don't annoy them with
a whole bunch of emails.

00:31:41.120 --> 00:31:42.867
We just put some big tables in.

00:31:42.867 --> 00:31:45.200
They sit with more people,
they get to know more people.

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:46.544
It feels like more of a team.

00:31:46.544 --> 00:31:47.960
So we act our way
to new thinking.

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:53.510
So at the end of the
day, partly because I

00:31:53.510 --> 00:31:55.540
was curious and not afraid
to say I don't know,

00:31:55.540 --> 00:31:57.140
I learned the ship.

00:31:57.140 --> 00:31:59.030
I learned it pretty well.

00:31:59.030 --> 00:32:01.550
My temptation was to
go back to be the old

00:32:01.550 --> 00:32:02.910
know all, tell all leader.

00:32:02.910 --> 00:32:06.010
Because I was firmly
rooted in that behavior.

00:32:06.010 --> 00:32:07.640
When I got stressed
out, I would always

00:32:07.640 --> 00:32:08.890
default back to that behavior.

00:32:08.890 --> 00:32:11.520
That was my default wiring.

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:13.850
If I hadn't slept
well, didn't eat well.

00:32:13.850 --> 00:32:15.590
My boss yelled at
me, so of course,

00:32:15.590 --> 00:32:18.680
I had to yell at my people.

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:21.680
But I'd seen the power of not
telling my people what to do.

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:26.030
Because I'd seen this explosion
in creativity and performance

00:32:26.030 --> 00:32:26.540
in the team.

00:32:26.540 --> 00:32:29.420
I saw the excitement
in their eyes.

00:32:29.420 --> 00:32:30.890
So I really resisted it.

00:32:30.890 --> 00:32:34.580
So now I tried as much as
possible to live over here.

00:32:34.580 --> 00:32:37.080
Even when I knew the answer and
they came up to me and said,

00:32:37.080 --> 00:32:38.600
well what do you
want us to do here,

00:32:38.600 --> 00:32:40.400
I would really
resist telling them.

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:43.100
Because over here, you
focus on ownership.

00:32:43.100 --> 00:32:44.764
Over here, you focus
on the long term.

00:32:44.764 --> 00:32:46.430
Over here you're
focusing on your people

00:32:46.430 --> 00:32:48.900
and developing
them into leaders.

00:32:48.900 --> 00:32:52.070
And yeah, some days you might
need to operate over here.

00:32:52.070 --> 00:32:53.790
But here's task accomplishment.

00:32:53.790 --> 00:32:54.774
This is short term.

00:32:54.774 --> 00:32:56.690
This is where, unfortunately,
a lot of leaders

00:32:56.690 --> 00:32:58.520
live all the time.

00:32:58.520 --> 00:33:01.820
You should decide where
you want to be here.

00:33:01.820 --> 00:33:02.574
You should decide.

00:33:02.574 --> 00:33:04.490
It shouldn't be determined
just by whether you

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:05.450
know the answer or not.

00:33:05.450 --> 00:33:07.824
Most leaders, if they know
the answer, they operate here.

00:33:07.824 --> 00:33:09.710
If they don't,
they operate here.

00:33:09.710 --> 00:33:11.145
They're down here, right?

00:33:11.145 --> 00:33:12.770
I can't tell you,
because I don't know.

00:33:12.770 --> 00:33:14.850
Or sometimes they operate here.

00:33:14.850 --> 00:33:19.190
I don't know, but I'm
still going to tell you.

00:33:19.190 --> 00:33:22.250
Myth number six, leaders
know all, tell all.

00:33:22.250 --> 00:33:24.650
The fact is the right
place for a leader

00:33:24.650 --> 00:33:27.290
to be is to still know your job.

00:33:27.290 --> 00:33:30.732
I'm not saying the lesson
is not don't know your job.

00:33:30.732 --> 00:33:33.190
That's what it took for me to
understand the power of this,

00:33:33.190 --> 00:33:34.090
though.

00:33:34.090 --> 00:33:37.170
But to resist giving
your team the answer.

00:33:37.170 --> 00:33:39.360
So one last poll, one last poll.

00:33:39.360 --> 00:33:43.702
A lot of what I'm talking about
is about giving up control.

00:33:43.702 --> 00:33:46.160
So I want you to think, and
again push in a bunch of words.

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:48.118
In fact take 30 seconds,
talk to your neighbor.

00:33:48.118 --> 00:33:50.900
And then together, let's put in
a bunch of words about what it

00:33:50.900 --> 00:33:52.820
feels like to give up control.

00:33:52.820 --> 00:33:57.470
Here's the thing I tell my
CEOs that I'm coaching to do.

00:33:57.470 --> 00:33:58.700
I say, you can go to dinner.

00:33:58.700 --> 00:34:01.322
Next time you go out to
eat, you don't get to order.

00:34:01.322 --> 00:34:03.530
I want you to just turn to
the waiter or the waitress

00:34:03.530 --> 00:34:06.590
and say, pick my meal.

00:34:06.590 --> 00:34:09.071
They're all control freaks,
so this freaks them out.

00:34:09.071 --> 00:34:11.570
So I want you to get that in
your head and think about that,

00:34:11.570 --> 00:34:12.879
and set up a bunch of words.

00:34:12.879 --> 00:34:13.670
See what we've got.

00:34:32.020 --> 00:34:33.650
Yeah, this is coming out.

00:34:33.650 --> 00:34:34.179
I love it.

00:34:34.179 --> 00:34:35.800
Because look what we got.

00:34:35.800 --> 00:34:42.340
Scary, risk, losing.

00:34:42.340 --> 00:34:44.960
We're going to lose control.

00:34:44.960 --> 00:34:50.469
At the same time, I
have trust and freedom

00:34:50.469 --> 00:34:57.780
and other good things.

00:34:57.780 --> 00:35:01.440
They're all coming
up on the screen.

00:35:01.440 --> 00:35:05.552
These words here, this
is how I felt every day

00:35:05.552 --> 00:35:06.510
as a submarine captain.

00:35:06.510 --> 00:35:09.240
Every day when I was
trusting my team,

00:35:09.240 --> 00:35:12.150
every day when I was saying
you guys get to choose,

00:35:12.150 --> 00:35:16.770
this is how I felt. I
felt for a long time

00:35:16.770 --> 00:35:20.040
that these were
the wrong feelings.

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:25.170
That I was doing something
wrong, because I felt this way.

00:35:25.170 --> 00:35:26.940
I was a little bit
nervous and scared.

00:35:26.940 --> 00:35:32.880
I call it the suck air
through teeth maneuver.

00:35:32.880 --> 00:35:34.390
That's your call.

00:35:34.390 --> 00:35:36.697
See what you guys do with that.

00:35:36.697 --> 00:35:39.030
But I now think this is
actually the way you're supposed

00:35:39.030 --> 00:35:41.600
to feel every day as a leader.

00:35:41.600 --> 00:35:43.920
Every day, if you
don't feel like you're

00:35:43.920 --> 00:35:46.536
on the verge of
this, then you're

00:35:46.536 --> 00:35:47.910
playing it too
close to the vest.

00:35:47.910 --> 00:35:48.940
You're too in control.

00:35:48.940 --> 00:35:50.730
You're too comfortable and
you're not building a team.

00:35:50.730 --> 00:35:51.563
It's just about you.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:57.570
So the final thing here is we
talk about oh, trust your gut,

00:35:57.570 --> 00:35:58.980
trust your instincts.

00:35:58.980 --> 00:36:01.740
But part of
leadership is feeling

00:36:01.740 --> 00:36:04.050
the way you're programmed
as a human to feel.

00:36:04.050 --> 00:36:06.540
Because you're program
to want to be in control

00:36:06.540 --> 00:36:09.090
and to reduce uncertainty.

00:36:09.090 --> 00:36:13.710
It's wading into that,
leaning into that discomfort

00:36:13.710 --> 00:36:19.710
and acting contrary to how your
gut might take you many times.

00:36:19.710 --> 00:36:23.070
Because it's not normal to
put your life in the hands

00:36:23.070 --> 00:36:25.380
of some other person.

00:36:25.380 --> 00:36:30.450
You're not biologically
wired to like that.

00:36:30.450 --> 00:36:33.139
But I think this
is the real way.

00:36:33.139 --> 00:36:34.430
This is why leadership is hard.

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:36.762
That's why we have so
few really good leaders.

00:36:36.762 --> 00:36:38.470
Because you have to
act contrary to that.

